\n                                        arization front end with a challenge-adapted Qwen3-ASR-1.7B\n                                                                                                                  Our SD ASR system, denoted SQZ-Qwen-ASR-1.7B, tar-\n                                        recognizer. The diarization front end performs voice activity\n                                                                                                             gets Task 1 only. On the diarization side, we build a modular\n                                        detection, subsegment generation, CAMPPlus speaker embed-\n                                                                                                             front-end within the 3D-Speaker framework [2] that performs\n                                        ding extraction, two-speaker spectral clustering, and RTTM-\n                                                                                                             voice activity detection (VAD), CAMPPlus speaker embedding\n                                        based audio segmentation. The resulting speaker-attributed seg-\n                                                                                                             extraction, and spectral clustering with the speaker count ﬁxed\n                                        ments are grouped by language or region and decoded by the\n                                                                                                             to two, followed by RTTM-driven audio cutting. On the recog-\n                                        adapted ASR model. For ASR adaptation, we ﬁrst perform su-\narXiv:2607.08208v1 [cs.CL] 9 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                             nition side, we start from the Qwen3-ASR-1.7B speech LLM\n                                        pervised full ﬁne-tuning on the ofﬁcial training data, then apply\n                                                                                                             [3] and adapt it to the MLC-SLM task setting through a three-\n                                        LoRA ﬁne-tuning with synthetic speech generated by a three-\n                                                                                                             stage recipe: full supervised ﬁne-tuning (SFT) on the ofﬁ-\n                                        pipeline TTS-based synthetic speech augmentation framework,\n                                                                                                             cial training set, low-rank adaptation (LoRA) [4] on synthetic\n                                        and ﬁnally reﬁne the model using GRPO reinforcement learn-\n                                                                                                             speech, and Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) re-\n                                        ing with rewards based on WER/CER and penalties for hallu-\n                                                                                                             inforcement learning that penalizes hallucinated and repetitive\n                                        cination, repetition, and length deviation. On the ofﬁcial de-\n                                                                                                             outputs. To feed the LoRA stage, we construct a three-pipeline\n                                        velopment set, the full system achieves an average tcpMER of\n                                                                                                             TTS-based synthetic speech augmentation framework around\n                                        23.70, reducing the error rate by 6.83 absolute points relative to\n                                  